result.execSummary:
Nikki Segner was extradited to another county, state or jurisdiction. Extradition means Nikki Segner was accused or convicted of an offense in another county, state or jurisdiction and was taken there to face their charge(s) or conviction.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: 9:50 am - Defendant Nikki Segner appeared, in custody.  Kristi S. Tlusty appeared by telephone for the State of Wisconsin.  Complaint acknowledged, reading waived.  Court questions defendant regarding waiver of extradition form and rights initialed by defendant.  Defendant signs waiver of extradition form.  Court finds waiver has been given freely and voluntarily and orders that she be released to agents of Minnesota.  Court orders defendant to be held for a period of 15 days in order for pickup from Minnesota otherwise defendant shall be released.  Adj. 9:55 am.
